[^6]: Although it cannot be called open data, there are cases where the cost of maintaining and managing the data provision system is covered by collecting fees from a limited group of users.

[^7]: For data created for administrative purposes in the future, it is necessary to ensure that data is prepared with the expectation that it will be published as open data in accordance with these guidelines. The Cabinet Secretariat IT Strategic Headquarters is required to monitor the status of preparation by each ministry and agency and make necessary adjustments.

[^8]: If data cannot be published as open data due to laws or reasonable grounds (including cases where there are restrictions on secondary use), this must be specifically indicated.

[^9]: If disclosing the reason for not publishing would itself reveal information that cannot be disclosed (non-disclosure information), the reason does not have to be published.

[^10]: This broadly includes websites, database sites, and individual business sites on the Internet established under the name of each ministry or agency (including affiliated organizations, local branch offices, and organizations belonging to ministries and agencies).

[^11]: Rules regarding the use of each ministry and agency's website, presented as a unified template to promote secondary use of data published on government agency websites. See Attachment 1 "Government Standard Terms of Use (Version 2.0)" of the "Basic Approach to Data Publication by Ministries and Agencies for the Promotion of Secondary Use (Guidelines)".

[^12]: For example, statistical data published by each ministry and agency.

[^13]: Data that needs to be updated at regular intervals, such as event information, congestion rates of public transportation, or disaster and disaster prevention information.

